President Joe Biden has announced his intention to nominate Bill Nelson as the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) Administrator. Bill Nelson is a former U.S. Senator and a fifth-generation Floridian with a long history of public service. He has served in various capacities, including in the state legislature, U.S. Congress, and as State Treasurer. Nelson has extensive experience in government policy, particularly in areas such as defense, intelligence, foreign policy, finance, commerce, and healthcare. He has also played a significant role in shaping space and science law, including the passage of the landmark NASA bill of 2010. Nelson himself flew on the 24th flight of the Space Shuttle in 1986, conducting medical experiments and research during the mission. He is widely regarded as a leading authority on the nation's space program and currently serves on the NASA Advisory Council.